          <FAQ title="What kinds of videos do you produce?">
            <p>
              I focus on technical videos used for developer onboarding,
              enablement, product demos, and customer success.
            </p>
            <p>
              This includes documentation walkthroughs, feature demos,
              getting-started series, integration guides, and internal or
              external enablement libraries.
            </p>
          </FAQ>

          <FAQ title="Do we need existing content to get started?">
            <p>
              Existing docs or demos help you move faster, but it’s not a hard
              requirement. If you have material, we can convert it directly into
              video. If not, we’ll shape a lightweight outline first.
            </p>
          </FAQ>

          <FAQ title="Do engineers need to be involved or appear on camera?">
            <p>No. Engineers do not need to be on camera.</p>
            <p>
              In most cases, involvement is limited to a short setup call and a
              single review pass to confirm technical accuracy. The goal is to
              remove engineers as a production bottleneck, not create a new one.
            </p>
          </FAQ>

          <FAQ title="How does pricing work for this kind of engagement?">
            <p>
              Most projects are scoped and priced as a fixed engagement based on
              the type and volume of videos.
            </p>
            <p>
              For early-stage teams or exploratory work, I can also work in
              shorter discovery or advisory phases. You’ll always get a clear
              estimate before we start.
            </p>
          </FAQ>

          <FAQ title="How long does it take to produce videos?">
            <p>
              Timelines depend on scope, but once inputs are available,
              production typically moves quickly.
            </p>
            <p>
              The more established your docs and environments are, the faster we
              can ship. Most teams see usable output within weeks, not months.
            </p>
          </FAQ>

          <FAQ title="How do reviews and revisions work?">
            <p>
              I aim for a single structured review pass focused on technical
              accuracy and clarity.
            </p>
            <p>
              Clear alignment up front usually prevents heavy revisions. If
              changes are needed, we handle them quickly and asynchronously.
            </p>
          </FAQ>

          <FAQ title="How do you communicate and collaborate during projects?">
            <p>
              I work async-first and adapt to whatever tools your team already
              uses, such as Slack, Linear, or Notion.
            </p>
            <p>
              The goal is low coordination overhead and clear visibility into
              progress.
            </p>
          </FAQ>
